{
  "text": "Here, the upper bound is already close to the given lower bound, which arises from Lower Bound (12). For all even n for which \u03c7 (K n ) = \u03c7 (K n ), however, the upper bound can be improved by one, because \u03c7 (K n ) = n \u2212 1 for even n. The problem is that the conjectured equality \u03c7 (K n ) = \u03c7 (K n ) is hard to prove in general. In [CITATION_1] , we could only prove it under the additional assumption that n \u2212 1 is an odd prime. Moreover, from the outset, this approach to improve the upper bound n + 2t is restricted to even n, because \u03c7 (K n ) = n for odd n. Nevertheless, the upper bound might be improvable for all n, as Conjecture 2.1 suggests. Indeed, at least for t = 1, this is the case:",
